Given the date has been set for end of March based on latest parliament vote - I think this deserves quite a bit of weight. Possible the thorny issue of the right of diaspora to vote may cause an issue but no indication it will cause any escalation at this point.

I watched @preciselylogan 's video which gave me one datapoint of the outside view -- in which 61.8% of elections scheduled over the last year or so were postponed due to COVID-19 or so. Not a perfect outside view but certainly one to keep in mind. Further, I referred to @mattlerner 's comment which suggested in Lebannon the base rate for non-postponement is 70%. I give much more credence to that metric so wanted to heavily weigh my outside view there to begin. So I started at 70% and then took some off given Logan's datapoint. So starting off I'll give the Before Apri the highest likelihood. Beyond that, I'm giving the "not before June 1" a slightly larger likelihood of happening given the country's motivation not to host the election during the fasting month of Ramandan -- which takes a lot of time off the table for the "Between April, May" option. That said, I've also referred to a couple of articles (https://www.reuters.com/markets/asia/lebanese-president-baulks-march-polls-amid-economic-meltdown-2021-11-19/ and https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/geagea-says-delaying-vote-would-condemn-lebanon-slow-death-2021-11-30/) which do suggest some likelihood of a postponement -- or at least some contempt for the March date. For now, I'll stick to a ~2/3 chance it's ontime with a 1/3 chance is gets postponed, with a skew towards June+.

Since elections started being held again in 1992, there have been only six (!), an average of about 0.3 a year, so naively I'd imagine a 2.5% chance in any given month, and a 10% chance of them being held before April. But that's a bit stupid, seeing as how a date has already been set! (https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2021/10/19/lebanon-sets-march-date-parliamentary-election).

Explanation video here: https://youtu.be/HOZiVAw27C8 -- Bumped my outcome up confidence in the first bucket up some as the crowd moves towards it and we get closer to March with no contradicting information.

After the end of the civil war, the first general elections were held at 1992. If elections would have followed without disruptions, there would have been 7 general elections already. Instead, there has only been 5 held in time, so roughly 70% of elections were in time. I would adjust on this rate somewhat, since there was another state's military presence inside the country for long, which makes this rate not so convincing. But for the time being I do not know how to update this.

The 2022 Lebanese general election is the upcoming general election in Lebanon, scheduled for March 27, 2022. The election was originally set to take place in May 8. However, Lebanon’s parliament has voted to set a date of March 27 next year to hold a parliamentary election. Due to the ongoing political and economic crisis, as well as the controversial electoral law, there has been speculation that the election could be postponed. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2022_Lebanese_general_election
There has only been two previous instances of election postponement in Lebanon ( 1972-1992 and 2007-2018)

Elections are scheduled for 27th March.
